What Stresses Us Out + How We Deal with It

A design research and visualization project by Yvette Shen, Elizabeth Sanders, Anne Knellinger, Deanna Sagaris, and Kaixin Luo.

We are exploring the problems students face in their everyday lives that elicit stress and anxiety, as well as their experiences and strategies of dealing with these problems.

We will use the results of this research project to design a supportive community that promotes positive thinking and positive behaviors in the future. We will do so by co-designing with OSU students and mental-health providers. We call this project Design for the Pursuit of Happiness.

Research Roadmap

About Co-Design

Co-design brings the people who will be served by design directly into the process as participants. In Design for the Pursuit of Happiness, OSU students and mental health providers will be the co-designers. Co-design acknowledges that everyone who is impacted by what is designed should play a central role in the design process.

We conducted three co-design sessions with a total of 23 participants who were undergraduate students of different levels (freshmen to seniors) and majors at The Ohio State University. Then we organized and analyzed the different types of data from the sessions in order to identify the emerging patterns.

In the co-design process, designers create different toolkits for non-designers to use to express themselves creatively. In our co-design session with students, we designed toolkits based on quantifiable charts and diagrams for the purpose of answering these research questions.

Research Roadmap

Data Results

1What are the patterns of students’ daily stress experiences?
Based on the results from the Daily Wellbeing Journey toolkit (Toolkit A), the research team identified different patterns of the ups and downs of the stress level in a day. These patterns lead to four types of personas as described in the graph below. Personas are fictional characters created based on research data that represent different user types in a design process. Personas help designers to recognize that different people have different needs and expectations.

2What are the stress levels students experienced with different academic components?
Based on the completed Toolkit B- Students’ Academic Stress, the graph below displays students’ responses to various academic stressors. We provided the following components: presentations, homework, projects, quizzes, mid-terms/finals in the toolkit. The empty boxes on the toolkit invited participants to write in additional academic stressors.

3What are the intensity and frequency levels of different stressors?
Based on the completed Toolkit C - Stress Intensity + Frequency, the graph below shows both how intense and how frequent different stressors are for the students. Students were also asked to rank the severity of the stressors using color-coding dot stickers.
Academics Physical and Mental Health Social Connections Future, Career, and Finance Personal
Fine without making any extra effort. Need to make extra efforts (mainly self-coping strategies). Currently seeing or considering seeking professional help.
4What are the most popular coping strategies that students consider to be effective? Not effective? Interested in trying?
Toolkit D asks students how they cope with stress. A packet of pre-printed labels with some common strategies was provided. Students were also asked to write-in their own coping strategies. This activity intends to understand the effectiveness of coping strategies that help college students to deal with stress, as well as gather more coping strategies.
Additional Highlights:

Some additional strategies provided by students include: "Being Active", "Writing Music", "Hammocking", "Taking Showers or Bath".

Some strategies work sometimes, some strategies are continue being practiced but students don't know how effective they actually are.

Moms are the most popular family members to talk to.

What's Next?

Co-designing with students about wellness has been the first step in this project. The second step will be to co-design with campus wellness health providers. They will share their views of students’ wellness health needs based on their observations and experiences. So then we will be able to directly compare the perspectives of the students and the wellness staff.

The final co-design session will bring together students and the wellness staff. We will share a summary demonstrating what students need with regard to their mental well-being and what services are offered currently by the wellness health centers on campus. The students and staff will identify and discuss the gaps between the two perspectives. The final step will be to invite them to imagine and express the ideal future for a well-supported college community that stimulates positive thinking and positive activities among the students, faculty and staff.
